item.title: Python all() Function Code Examples
item.description: all() is a Python built-in function to return True if all elements of the iterable argument are True or the iterable argument is empty. all() with list of all True values data_list = [True, True, True] x = all(data_list) print(x) Output: True all() with list of not all True values data_list = [False, True, True] x = all(data_list) print(x) Output: False all() with list of all False values data_list = [False, False, False] x = all(data_list) print(x) Output:
